Parliament did not support an amendment to free Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian Parliament has today rejected the proposal to repeal the amendment of the section of the Criminal Code in which the opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko is sentenced.
The modification would open the doors to the release of the former prime minister, but the parliamentarians rejected the proposal to reduce the sentences for economic crimes in the second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for allegedly signing an agreement with Russia that was disadvantageous for Ukraine on the purchase of natural gas.
The sentence is not yet final, the appeal court has the obligation to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that it was a political revenge of the regime, and even in the West doubts have arisen about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to withdraw paragraph 365 of the Criminal Code with which the former prime minister was sentenced was supported by 147 deputies in the vote.
For its approval, 226 votes were required.
