Brand story:
Innovative IBM enters its second century of existence
If someone were looking for a term that defined IBM&#39;s strategy with great precision, the closest would be &quot;long term.&quot;
For the general public, IBM is the symbol of a technological revolution, a company that is perceived as current and yet a hundred years have passed since its founding.
The basis of this long-term character was laid by the first head of the firm, the visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He already coined the motto that many of the world&#39;s problems can be solved if people are willing to think.
His motto &quot;Think!&quot; it became his seal, around which the life of the future giant will be built (it was also the title of an internal magazine that IBM began to publish in 1935).
Watson was also the foundation of a carefully crafted company culture.
&quot;For us, IBM means long-term thinking, a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM has survived and prospered for a hundred years for that reason, because it stayed true to its core principles, but was unafraid of the changes around it.
That has allowed us, during our first century, to transform technology, business and society.
We hope to prosper even more in our second century,&quot; said the current director of the company, Samuel J. Palmisano, during its anniversary.
A sophisticated system
Watson, as early as the 1930s, cared about the care of his employees as the businessman from Baťa in the Czech Republic (IBM employees were among the first American workers to enjoy paid vacations, insurance, elegant uniforms and a sophisticated remuneration system that rewarded the best inventors and salesmen.
The same long-term sophistication is maintained by IBM in the relationship with the client.
From the beginning the company knew how to discover talents (being one of the first companies in the world to put an end to any type of discrimination, it could choose without problems).
IBM&#39;s current plan is in line with the anti-discrimination strategy, whereby Palmisano will be replaced next year by a woman: Virginia Rometty.
She has now worked for thirty years at IBM, where she has been head of sales, marketing and strategy.
During the last few years, IBM has participated in the so-called virtual meetings, online brainstorming, from which an infinite number of future strategies and innovations emerge.
It is not surprising that there are plenty of ideas, since almost half a million people work in the firm.
An institution with a good reputation
The fixed position in the business provides the company with a strong internal and external image.
&quot;From the beginning, IBM was more of an institution than a technology company,&quot; says Harvard Business School economist and author of the book on IBM Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
&quot;IBM is not a technology company, but a company that tries to solve business problems for technology users,&quot; says George Colony of Forrester Research consultancy.
As the company itself says, there is a difference between entering the business and directly creating a business.
IBM - or &quot;Big Green&quot; - as it is familiarly known in the US because of its logo, has become one of the world&#39;s largest companies in the last hundred years.
It is possibly the most versatile technological company (it develops both equipment and programs, infrastructures and web hosting services within a wide range of services, ranging from servers to nanotechnology).
It holds the largest number of patents of any North American technology company and five of its employees have received the Nobel Prize.
Among his inventions are the ATM, payment cards, financial swaps, barcodes, and floppy disks.
IBM will bill this year 220 billion dollars. This year it has become the second technology firm by market capitalization (the first is Apple), when it surpassed Microsoft for the first time in 1996.
Looking at the future
Not all products and innovations just satisfy the taste of customers and the moment (IBM did not bet on its own operating system, OS/2, Prodigy online services or IBM PCjr computers).
&quot;If your business is based on moving forward, you can&#39;t be emotionally anchored in the past,&quot; recognized Samuel J. Palmisano.
For this reason, IBM has no problem building its foundations on other platforms (and equally, if they don&#39;t work, it abandons them).
And this sets it apart from the competition, Microsoft, which basically stands and falls always exclusively with Windows.
future technology
In terms of sales, IBM is primarily engaged in services, of which about one-fifth are software and another fifth are hardware.
Yet even in 1990 equipment represented more than half of the supplier&#39;s share.
Starting in the year 2000, IBM has sold underperforming assets worth a total of $15 billion. During the same period, it has invested 58 billion dollars in the purchase of future technology.
Investments have continued since 2008, when the modern global financial crisis first manifested itself.
IBM acts according to the premises of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who during the great economic crisis of 1929 increased investments.
It seems that until now the IBM company has managed to weather the crisis.
The value of IBM shares since the beginning of 2008 has grown stratospherically up to 120%, the net profit of the company has not stopped increasing.
IBM&#39;s motto is to change everything except its value.
It can therefore be expected that when the next crisis comes, this flexible giant will hold on.
IBM history: from the cheese slicer to spaceflight
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York one hundred years ago, its original name being Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM is adopted as early as 1924 - originally it was a brand name used in branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation that gave rise to the birth of IBM arises from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
He had inventions such as the famous &quot;clock clock&quot;, which allows controlling the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was the businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired its supervisory board.
Flint recruited the head of a competing company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The new leader eclipsed the founder of IBM (Watson&#39;s ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are based).
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name indicates, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business gadgets, from meat and cheese slicers to cash registers.
During the first four years that Watson led the company, revenues doubled to $9 million and the company&#39;s great expansion across continents began.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, after almost forty years in the chief&#39;s chair, he was succeeded by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his direction, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM staff and computers helped NASA guide flights into space (to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic &quot;fish&quot;, which set the standard for computers at the time, hit the market under the name of the IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its production of computers to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, for its part, acquired the consulting part of the Pricewaterhouse Coopers company and began to offer comprehensive advice and high value-added services.
The strategy that IBM has paid for in the last three years is the Smarter Planet concept, that is, &quot;a smarter planet.&quot;
Its aim is to make a more rational use of technology, although areas have not yet been planned and circumstances have not been improved, for example, with regard to transport and city administration.
For the commerce sector, IBM recently introduced the &quot;Smart Commerce&quot; platform that enables retailers to manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
Already in 1932 it opened a branch in the then Czechoslovakia, the first country to have one in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today IBM ČR also operates the strategic outsourcing center in Brno here.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is in Prague. Also here is a world famous research team working with speech recognition.
