How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia at that time: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies at that time sold trips in most cases only to the socialist bloc, since trips to the West were highly restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on vacation to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea on the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both on the Black Sea) and to Hungary ( Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when travel to Yugoslavia was possible, however, after the Yugoslav regime leaned west and travel by Czech tourists was then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that citizens of the socialist bloc (ie also Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even in socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West in those days, but one had to get in line with a sleeping bag and spend the whole night like that, or have &quot;good acquaintances&quot; at the agency.
Even so, not everything was won.
The so-called &quot;promise of change&quot; which was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to &quot;politically unreliable people&quot;, who thus could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, and without a guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of the Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired. This custom still persists.
The Czech way of traveling has undergone a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was the ultimate holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million holiday trips to countries all over the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, that the currently favorite destination, Croatia, was not freely travelable until 1989, because it was part of Yugoslavia at that time.
In the early 1990s, visa exemptions were imposed to travel to neighboring Western European states, which led to a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not see themselves fed up with excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris groups of Czechs slept in the parks in tents, since our income at that time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or pension.
A typical characteristic of the Czechs at that time was taking food with them (canned food, sausages, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy western currency.
Our standard of living was rising and with it average wages, which around 1997 led to an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increase in the demand for travel, agencies began, from 1997 on a regular basis, to prepare trips using charter flight connections, which made the prices of trips drop dramatically compared to the past, thanks to the possibility to obtain discounts for the volume of passengers.
At the end of the 90s of the last century, the Czechs already traveled without a visa to almost all developed countries, except the USA, which further simplified our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened already in 2000, when the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country was organized thanks to huge demand, and it went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists have departed every year for distant and hot countries. This winter it will already be flown directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this time, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in the year 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US abolished visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008 the Czechs, for the first time in their history, spent more than half of their vacations abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they spent more than 15,000 kronor on trips abroad. checks per head, including expenses at the place of stay.
Ordinary General Assembly convened to elect the president, which could end up in deadlock again.
For almost five months, Czech football has been without a president and it is likely that the successor to Ivan Hašek as President of the Czech Football Federation (FAČR) will not be known even after the convening of the next Extraordinary General Assembly that will take place this Thursday. in Nymburk.
In fact, no agreement has yet been reached on the voting rules to be followed.
Without them, you will not be able to vote even to choose between the three candidates.
Those interested in presiding over Czech football are Jindřich Rajchl, Miroslav Pelta and Tomáš Paclík.
Hašek resigned from his position in June but not before calling his colleagues together with the aim of finding a strong person who would know how to deal with football in the future.
However, after the Hašek era concluded, a controversy broke out between the two association federations unable to reach an agreement to choose a common candidate.
This became evident on September 16 when the new president had to be elected.
Delegates to the General Assembly met in vain at the National House (Národní dům), located in the Prague neighborhood of Smíchov, because the talks had stalled, and not only regarding the method of election.
No consensus was reached as to who in the General Assembly had the right to vote - only the legal representatives or also the delegates with full powers.
From that moment and due to this single point, a partial agreement was produced, also supported by the recommendation of the Institute of State and Law, according to which representation by full powers is not possible.
However, disputes over the electoral code remain open.
Not even the Executive Committee could shed more light on the situation, which, in its ordinary or extraordinary meetings, basically did not resolve anything.
The opinion on the possibility of voting has changed a couple of times already, but the nerve center remains the same.
The question is this: how to proceed in the third round to avoid deadlock?
&quot;The dispute revolves around whether to proceed according to the statutes or find another model,&quot; says Dušan Svoboda, one of FAČR&#39;s three vice-presidents, who, from the association&#39;s leadership, represents professional football.
According to the model proposed in the statutes, in the third round the candidate who has the highest percentage of support in the federation to which he will present his candidacy will win.
The Moravian Region is willing to reach a compromise so that the candidate with the highest total percentage of votes in both federations can win.
The Bohemian party, however, imposes the condition that the winner, according to these percentage calculations, must have a majority of at least two thirds.
&quot;This would, however, take away the meaning of the two previous rounds and would completely negate the concept of a bicameral system&quot;, this is how Svoboda understands the objections of the Moravian party, according to which it would be best not to touch the order and vote under applicable statutes.
With what has been said, surprisingly, Tomaš Paclík also agrees, although it is assumed that the electoral regulations established by the statutes of all the candidates are more convenient for Pelta.
&quot;I would like to see the maximum vote in accordance with the statutes.&quot;
&quot;So that they don&#39;t come up with any nonsense about the representatives like in the last General Assembly,&quot; says the owner of Victoria Plzen, who is running for the first time as a candidate and who directs his remarks mainly against Pelta.
Pelta remains optimistic.
According to him, the new president will be decided in Nymburk and he believes that the candidates in the future will cooperate constructively.
&quot;All passions will be appeased by today&#39;s match of our national team in the European Championship.
&quot;Football will once again be the protagonist, and thus cooperation will be more comfortable,&quot; says the representative of Jablonice, who of the three candidates has the most experience in football management, both at a professional and regional level.
Rajchl is the most reticent.
&quot;I hope an agreement is reached, but unfortunately the situation is much more complicated.&quot;
&quot;It&#39;s not about the conflict between Bohemians and Moravians, but there are attempts to adjust the rules to suit their own convenience.&quot;
&quot;This may result in a new blockade of the General Assembly.&quot;
&quot;Still, I hope common sense will prevail,&quot; Rajchl said.
There is not much time left for all parties to come to an agreement.
Some negotiations had to take place in Montenegro, but who can know until the game starts if the football team will be complete?
The special plane, in which the vice presidents Dalibor Kucera and Rajchl, among others, had to travel to Podgorica, did not leave this morning due to technical problems in Prague, having to find an alternative to transport part of the executive committee to the place where it will take place the qualifying match.
Perhaps the decisive meeting, finally, could be the one that will take place at the ministerial level, which, according to what they say, will be held this Wednesday.
Josef Dobeš, Minister of Education, Youth and Sports, would very much like to bring the divided parties into the most powerful sports organization in the country so that an agreement can be reached.
There is a lot at stake: state subsidies, the credibility of football and also the next General Assembly of the Central Committee of the Czechoslovak Sports Federation (ČSTV) that will try to give a new direction to Czech sports after the financial problems of the lottery house Sazka.
