House 21 in Vienna
The moved pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
A story of architecture with ups and downs and a happy ending, the pavilion at the 1958 Austrian World&#39;s Fair in Brussels won awards, was in Vienna for a museum, stood empty and fell into disrepair.
It is now reopened as an exhibition house.
Post-modern architecture fascinates, the clear shapes, the glass halls, the courageous curves and the new building materials, typical of the thinking about technical progress, for which the Austrian pavilion of the architect Karl Schwanzer for the World&#39;s Fair Brussels of 1958 is an apt and familiar example.
The Schwanzer Pavilion then won the Architecture Grand Prix for its light, floating steel and glass construction.
The construction is considered to this day a contemporary landmark of architecture.
He made the architect so well known that he also built the Austrian pavilion at the next World&#39;s Fair.
With his legendary four-cylinder tower for MBW plus the flattened adjacent building in Munich, he became internationally known.
Its pavilion, designed as a temporary construction for exhibitions, was erected after the World&#39;s Fair in the Schweizer Garten next to the Vienna South Station, was renovated in 1962 and a 20th-century museum was opened inside, it was called the &quot;house 20 &quot;.
The building was adequate but lacked the proper spaces and technology for a museum; without any wall to hang art, nor a good atmosphere.
Despite this, it was used until contemporary art in Vienna had a new home.
The building has been empty since 2001 and is increasingly decaying.
Currently, the architect Adolf Krischanitz renovated the pavilion, he now calls it &quot;house 21&quot; and it will be used in the future as a museum for contemporary art.
On Tuesday afternoon the belvedere museum, to which the house belongs, opened with the first exhibition, a stroke of luck in a way.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, the new director of the Austrian belvedere gallery since 2007, has made a fresh start.
Husslein-Arco, a doctor of art history with a considerable career including, among other things, an ice skater in her youth, later at Sotheby&#39;s, the Guggenheim Museum and founding director of the Salzburg Museum of Modern Art, carried out the renovations with the At the insistence of politicians and protectors of the monuments, he provided public funds and private sponsors and established their use.
With the exception of contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba from the eponymous foundation are exhibited, there should be a cafeteria and a bookstore and an office building should also be built.
Tight control, low budget
Krischanitz was the best choice to do it.
Not only because he sensitively reformed the secession of Joseph Olbrichs in Vienna, expanded it and was awarded the competition, but because he studied with Schwanzwer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was for him an &quot;important and immense place&quot;, in which he contemplated &quot;almost every weekend&quot; the exhibitions.
He knew the project and the problem of the building, which disappeared with its transfer to Vienna in its change of use with generosity and ease.
There are big problems with the current renovations, the building was &quot;an energy hog&quot;, Krischanitz said.
The profile of the windows on the glass façade was changed, fiberglass reinforced insulating glass was installed and the glass roof was replaced with special security glass.
Thermal bridges and steel girders were reinforced or replaced, and asbestos roofs rehabilitated.
Two cellars were used for the new use, a light panel lowered between the house and the street provides lighting, a bridge serves to enter the almost new building, but still the Schwanzer pavilion.
Original exterior doors remain, house is painted in antique mahogany tones and protected against rust.
And the movie theater is exactly as it was before.
And all this with strict control by the monuments office and a low budget.
&quot;I often had to find material that was good, cheap and also liked by the monument protection office,&quot; says Krischanitz, warning of a rough floor in the basement.
Despite all the pressures, problems and reforms, the building remains flexible and light.
The pavilion &quot;that came from Brussels&quot; has been difficult, Krischanitz said recently, a typical &quot;chance appearance in the history of the city.&quot;
Such an architecture is &quot;always in the wrong place&quot; and for this reason he wanted to &quot;awaken the right conscience&quot;.
In this case, house 21 is not in the wrong place, an urban windfall has occurred. The completely new and planned &quot;central station district&quot; with housing and offices is located next to the Schweizer Garten.
And maybe another stroke of luck will happen: House 21 could receive a reinforcement from another Krischanitz construction, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg has bought the temporary art room in Berlin and, as you hear, is negotiating with the city about a neighboring place in the Schweizer Garten.
