Clever jackdaws spread in cities
In many places, jackdaws are considered &quot;problem birds&quot;: these highly intelligent animals are not being driven out of cities for a long time, experts say.
Some like them, others want to get rid of them very quickly, jackdaws have been part of the image of the city for years, but in many municipalities complaints from neighbors are piling up about the filth and noise of the animals.
Although no means against &quot;problem birds&quot; have appeared so far.
Jackdaws no longer leave the cities, experts say at the first jackdaw symposium in Leer, East Frisia.
There specialists from all over the national territory discuss possible solutions.
They look for alternatives in the cities
Ecologists attribute the problems of the cities to the migration from the countryside of certain protected rooks; chemical applications in agriculture are visibly destroying traditional living spaces.
Hunting, the increasing construction and the fall of trees that host them make life difficult for birds.
The jackdaws are protected.
There are large colonies with more than 600 breeding pairs in Soest, Westphalia, among others, in the northwest, among others in Jever, Diepholz and Achim in Bremen, as well as in Leer.
There, in 2005, a controversial project to mass-kill the district&#39;s rooks made negative headlines.
Critics have called the hunting of animals by trapping birds and killing them with sticks especially brutal.
&quot;Ejecting them and driving them away in the normal way does not achieve anything,&quot; said Werner Klöver, urban planner and landscape designer from Leer.
Shooting nests with water or knocking down trees are often unintended consequences, also says Manfred Kaiser, an environmental expert from Lahr, Baden-Württemberg.
&quot;The animals stray, the large colonies divide and distribute elsewhere.&quot;
Scaring them away is only imaginable as an exception in hospitals, nursing homes or schools.
&quot;We must live with them, we don&#39;t catch them anymore.&quot;
Without the surroundings, the problem in cities is not solved, says Wolfgang Kellner, Mayor of Leer.
A combination of driving animals away from sensitive residential areas and baiting them back to settle elsewhere is possible.
&quot;Information boards instead of chainsaws&quot; Uta Maria Jürgens, psychologist and ethnologist, advertises against the fact that animals are treated in a completely different way: &quot;The best thing is that we can take a pike in the face with aplomb.&quot;
Jürgens co-founded the Ascheberger Jackdaw Teaching Circuit in Schleswig-Holstein, where signs inform about the life of the intelligent birds.
Meanwhile, the project is accepted by tourists.
Jürgens also has his own take on the criticism of bird noise: &quot;It&#39;s all forms of communication, they have a lot to say.&quot;
The intelligence and skill of these animals are legendary, the jackdaws not only take advantage of the resources to access schist morsels, but also make tools to use them as resources.
Recently, ethologists from the University of Cambridge verified how far the intelligence of birds goes in four jackdaws.
In one experiment, birds quickly learned that they had to drop a rock on a platform to hit a moth larva.
Without much training, they determinedly recognized the size and shape the stone had to be to fall on the platform.
In a second trial, the cunning jackdaws had to solve a complicated problem.
The researchers placed a small cube with a moth larva in a vertical cylinder.
The birds could not reach their prey with their beaks.
But the researchers left them a piece of wire.
With which the four animals formed a hook, with which they fished the bucket into the tube handle.
Three of the four jackdaws got it on the first try.
