Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Are Studying You on Facebook
Before he became the new face of the far-right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just another guy airing his anti-immigration views online.
Breivik, who admitted to carrying out a massacre in Norway in July that left 77 dead, faced his first public court hearing on Monday.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of the time leading up to his attack in front of his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalist supporters of right-wing groups online. social.
After this summer&#39;s tragedy, investigators wanted to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - just log in to Facebook.
&quot;We found it wasn&#39;t that hard to reach them,&quot; says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European digital populism by UK think tank DEMOS.
Facebook&#39;s cache of personal information is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to pinpoint their desired demographics with scientific precision — the way marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett&#39;s team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then targeted ads at them, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey asking about their educational level, attitudes towards violence and optimism about their own future.
By reaching out via Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - all without leaving the office.
&quot;It&#39;s a whole new way of doing research,&quot; says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not entirely surprising: Online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, male, and angry about immigration.
However, in a twist of sorts, &quot;those who combine their online activism with their offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic, and less violent than those who stay behind the computer screen.&quot;
DEMOS&#39;s work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming an important new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists are using the site to study everything from health issues to social trends as expressed in likes, wall posts and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook&#39;s &quot;data supernova&quot; is spawning a research boom, driving the number of scholarly papers with the site&#39;s name in the title up to almost 800% in the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn&#39;t approach with a folder on the street.
&quot;Before, when you tried to survey people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them.&quot;
&quot;You&#39;d have to go through the party, and they&#39;d never let you in,&quot; says Bartlett.
&quot;Facebook removes all of that - you go to them directly.&quot;
Others say the site could provide a way to identify and address social-health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and colleagues found that college students who discussed their drunken exploits on Facebook had a significantly higher risk of problem drinking than students who they remained silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that the students&#39; peers, such as residential counselors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who posts too many binge status updates.
&quot;You can&#39;t treat a problem if you can&#39;t diagnose it,&quot; Dimitri Christakis, Moreno&#39;s co-author and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Children&#39;s Research Institute, told the Washington Post.
&quot;We have found a way to identify at-risk children who would otherwise go undiagnosed.&quot;
Facebook is also constantly &quot;probing&quot; its own population for data.
The site&#39;s Data Team has produced statistics on relationship status and Valentine&#39;s Day, expected voter turnout midway through the 2010 legislative term, and a National Happiness Index (primarily using data from can access - longtime advocates of digital freedom who argue that the site should make its vast amounts of data available to others for research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - the sacrifice of being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is allowing the site to mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don&#39;t even know about?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, online is an open bar for everyone.
&quot;I don&#39;t think many of the users have even thought about the fact that a researcher might be looking at their profiles,&quot; says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at London&#39;s Knowledge Lab, of a 2006 study he carried out on the walls. student Facebook audiences.
&quot;As far as they were concerned, it was just between them and their friends.&quot;
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research topic is being completely honest.
On Facebook, it&#39;s impossible to know which part of a user&#39;s profile information and wall posts are true.
&quot;What you say on Facebook and what you do off of Facebook are two completely different things,&quot; says Selwyn.
That&#39;s why, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn believes that a clipboard and pen are still the best investigative tools anyone can use.
&quot;There&#39;s no substitute for getting into the real world and talking to real people,&quot; he says.
&quot;Social research is supposed to be about the social - and a lot of the social still happens offline.&quot;
