7 Lessons From Lost Steve Jobs Interview Shown In Theater This Week
Following the death of Steve Jobs on October 5th, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford - distinguishing the technological genius as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find most revealing, in a recently rediscovered Jobs interview dusted off in advance of a series of special screenings in major markets this week, is just how much this creative mind understood about the processes. sales and product workflows.
He was certainly a self-acknowledged designer, dreamer and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and flowchart junkie - a man who believed that many executives suffered from &quot;a disease of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of work... [but] there is an enormous amount of work between a great idea and a great product.&quot;
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing The Triumph of the Nerds television series about the dawn of the personal computer, and he sat down with Jobs for over an hour for a long and rare conversation.
At that point, it had been barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced out of Apple, and he was already hard at work at his new computer company NeXT, hoping for popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of Cringely&#39;s interview was used in Nerds, he said that the originals of the interview disappeared during transport.
It was only after Jobs&#39; death that a complete VHS copy was discovered in the director&#39;s garage.
This slightly re-edited archival footage is the basis for the 68-minute Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which hits Landmark Theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expound on his technology philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there are long silences between questions and answers - 10 to 15 seconds of musing, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking precision.
There are also moments when Jobs&#39;s perfectionism surfaces, where he seems impatient with Cringely&#39;s questions, prompting him to move faster to the more important issues or arguments.
Shot before the era of Pixar, the iPod, or the iPhone, there&#39;s something strangely prescient about The Lost Interview, as Jobs weighs in on what he sees other companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
It&#39;s one thing to read posthumous assessments of Jobs&#39;s career, but there&#39;s something raw and inspiring about the Jobs we see here, the eager dreamer on the brink of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining it all in detail here, he went and did it.
A quick recap of seven notable sequences from The Lost Interview:
On how he learned to run a business:
&quot;Throughout my years in the business, I always asked, &#39;Why do you do things?&#39; and the answers you get invariably are, &quot;Oh, that&#39;s just the way it&#39;s done.&quot;
Nobody knows why they do what they do, in business nobody thinks about things very deeply.
That&#39;s what I found.
Jobs details his efforts to simplify Apple&#39;s accounting.
Baffled by the way costs were recorded - often starting with a &quot;standard cost&quot; that was done by eye, then adjusted with a &quot;variable&quot; - he developed an automated factory that claimed they could determine costs retail commercials.
On the prank on the Pope:
Jobs recounts the &quot;Blue Box&quot; he built himself with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack into the phone company and make free long-distance calls.
The device has been widely written about, but Jobs&#39; euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a pay phone, making a call, then connecting from one AT&amp;T network to another, while looping as many satellites as possible.
&quot;We were wrapping things around the world a half dozen times and you&#39;d yell into the pay phone and come back a minute later to the pay phone next door,&quot; Jobs says with a chuckle.
&quot;We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.&quot;
The two of us, we didn&#39;t know much, but we could build a small thing that could control a giant thing - it was an incredible lesson, and I don&#39;t think Apple would have ever existed without it.
Jobs goes on to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost gave up on, calling the Vatican via Blue Box in the middle of the night and requesting to speak to the Pope, while doing his best Henry Kissinger impression.
As various members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the US diplomat, the two burst out laughing just before the Pope himself was awakened to go answer the phone.
On falling in love with technology (and teleselling with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, on the hunt for replacement parts to build a frequency counter, he looked up Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made a call.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs landed a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
&quot;That was a huge influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my view of what a company was and how well they treated their employees.&quot;
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company&#39;s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw &quot;the first desktop computer ever made.&quot;
It was as big as a suitcase, had a little cathode tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I would get a trip to HP as a teenager and mess around with that machine and write programs for it.
On improvising innovation:
At various points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the fly.
Early in his career, as he was selling a handful of motherboards, he was asked by a customer if he could assemble all the equipment.
Working with only 30 days of credit, he had to figure out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
&quot;I remember having dramatic story lines...they yelled at me that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I got fed up and went out and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and it was completely reliable.
On big companies losing steam:
Long before he led Apple&#39;s renaissance, Jobs presciently foresaw how many industry leaders would stumble on his vision, losing control of their market share.
&quot;Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better copiers and printers, so what?&quot;
You have a monopoly on market share, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it is these kinds of people who end up running the companies and the people in charge of the products are thrown out of the decision-making forum.
The product genius that led to that monopoly position is rotting away from people who don&#39;t have the notion of good products vs bad products - the necessary trade knowledge.
That&#39;s what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They took defeat for victory.
On innovation as artistic expression:
&quot;There is a tremendous amount of work between a great idea and a great product...as the great idea evolves, it changes and grows.&quot;
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make - some things you can&#39;t make electrons do, glass does, robots do, factories do.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain - these concepts - adjust them all at once...
In the end it all comes down to taste - it boils down to trying to expose you to the best that a team of humans has done, and then trying to adapt those things to what you&#39;re doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We&#39;ve never been shy about stealing great ideas.
What made the Macintosh great in part was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who just happened to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it weren&#39;t for computing, I could be doing wonderful things in other fields.
