&quot;It&#39;s a brigade without bullets.&quot;
&quot;It&#39;s an air wing without enough trained pilots.&quot;
&quot;It&#39;s a paper tiger, an army of barracks, buildings and bombs without enough trained soldiers to accomplish the mission,&quot; Panetta said in his opening remarks at the Pentagon.
&quot;It is a force that suffers from low morale, poor preparation and is unable to keep up with potential adversaries.&quot;
&quot;Indeed, it invites aggression...&quot;
In an appendix to his letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta lays out new details of how the reductions &quot;create significant operational risks: delayed response time to crises, conflicts and disasters; severely limits our ability to be pre-deployed and engaged in everyone; and poses an unacceptable risk in future combat operations.&quot;
And Panetta said some of the biggest defense projects could face the axe, including those already being tested and some only in the early planning stages.
That list includes the F35 Joint Strike Fighter jet, a planned new bomber, the next-generation ballistic submarine, the new littoral combat ship, and the new ground combat vehicle the Army and Navy need to replace, the humvee.
