how to spot a lie
A glance at the most recent headlines tells us how serious and pervasive deceit and lies are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy trading sexual harassment allegations with several women; each party accuses the other of lying.
Administrators at Pennsylvania State University have been charged with perjury for allegedly concealing reports that a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was &quot;caught&quot; on an open microphone telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
The New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist, Anthony Weiner, made a fool of himself with his denials that were quickly refuted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign finance violations related to covering up an extramarital affair.
And again, no one who lived through it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton by lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about cheating in school and university exams are widespread.
There have been cases in which teachers have given exam answers to students in order to be better seen in their performance evaluations.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How deceitful are we?
On any given day, studies show that you can be lied to anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
That&#39;s for sure, many of those lies are white lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting.
Detecting lies, or &quot;lie spotting,&quot; is an essential skill that must be acquired by all of us, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, say, Charade, where the goal is to exclaim, &quot;I&#39;ve got you&quot;, deception detection is a serious body of knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the last six decades at prestigious universities that they conducted in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about lying have been disproved.
Liars do look into the eyes.
They don&#39;t always stutter, lisp, blush, or fidget.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can arrive at the truth by learning about statement structure, microfacial expressions, question formation, and tenses.
I spent several years plumbing the scientific findings on deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that deception detection is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world - especially if your responsibilities Professionals include hiring, interviewing, or managing negotiations.
Good liars have the ability to read others well, putting them at ease, managing their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more &quot;self-oriented lies&quot; while women tell more &quot;other-oriented&quot; lies -- usually to protect someone&#39;s feelings -- that married people lie less frequently to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they often tell tend to be &quot;huge&quot;).
We also know that if you are perceived as a wrongdoer, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the habitual behavior of the subject.
This is called &quot;creating a baseline.&quot;
It helps provide benchmarks for later measurement of changes.
Note the subject&#39;s posture, laugh, and vocal characteristic.
You better know if someone normally taps their feet all the time so you don&#39;t make unfair accusations when you see their feet tapping in the middle of the meeting.
Next, look for groups of deceptive behavior, verbal and non-verbal.
Consider these clusters of behavior as red flags, not evidence of deception.
People who cheat may freeze their upper body trying to recall their story, point their feet toward the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or exhibit &quot;post-interview vent&quot; -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all the hard questions are over.
Interrogators often falsely pretend that the interview is over just to seek post-interview relief.
Also pay attention to the vocabulary of the subject.
Scott Peterson botched it all the way and used the past tense while claiming his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide manhunt for her.
People who cheat may also use distancing language: &quot;I did not have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky&quot; or repeat a difficult question in full.
The most common verbal cues are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of &quot;restrictive language&quot; when answering a difficult question: &quot;Well...to tell you the truth...as far as I know...to the best of my knowledge.&quot;
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula to detect lies, but developing skills to detect deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone&#39;s chances of avoiding being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
