The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The designated prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the president of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has placed that country on the brink of economic disaster.
Italian Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet Italy&#39;s president on Wednesday to present the new government that will deal with a crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic disaster and jeopardized the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with the president, Giorgio Napolitano, on Wednesday to confirm that he can form a government.
He is expected to produce a cabinet made up mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he will present to the president the result of his talks with the political parties in his bid to form a government.
&quot;I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country&#39;s ability to overcome this difficult phase,&quot; the former European commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not say explicitly that he will be able to form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
The &quot;framework is now well outlined,&quot; he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than normal, as Italy battles a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a harsh austerity package demanded by European leaders to restore battered confidence in Italy.
Underscoring the pressure on Monti to hurry, unsteady markets pushed the yield on Italy&#39;s 10-year BTP bonds above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to be bailed out.
Emma Marcegaglia, the leader of the Italian employers&#39; association Confindustria, told reporters after meeting Monti: &quot;We said we would be very supportive of this government.&quot;
We believe that this Government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti&#39;s chances of success were boosted considerably by the PDL party backing of Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced by the crisis to resign on Saturday.
&quot;We believe that Professor Monti&#39;s efforts are destined to have a good result,&quot; Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told reporters.
The support of the PDL, Italy&#39;s largest party, is significant because until now many of its members have opposed the mostly technocratic government that Monti is forming.
parliamentary support
Monti&#39;s new government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in their efforts could spark a devastating new attack from the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure, warning that a failure by Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations on Monday with political parties, unions and business groups, as well as youth and women&#39;s organizations.
He will end his round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite late last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would step down, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty over whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Bailing out Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 trillion euros, would be too much for the eurozone&#39;s current financial defenses.
Monti has said his government should last until the next elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms before early elections.
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist it should consist only of technicians, an indication of their qualms about a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources pointed out that mutual mistrust and disagreements between parties are complicating the attempt to include political figures.
