Quintet included the country in its tour to celebrate two decades of experience
&quot;Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true&quot;
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said that the band is ready to offer one of its best concerts next Sunday, at the National Stadium.
It has been more than 20 years of waiting, but the band assures that for them it will also be to make the dream of playing in the country a reality.
This was stated by the bassist and founding member, Jeff Ament, who spoke exclusively with Viva, from Brazil, last week.
The group is in the South American wing of its tour to celebrate two decades of work and on Sunday the 20th it will make its only stop in Central America.
That day they will perform at the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 pm, together with the Los Angeles band The X and the nationals of Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which is in La Nación on the Internet.
For your Costa Rican fans, it is a dream come true that Pearl Jam is going to play in Costa Rica, are you aware of what your fans are experiencing?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is only our second time in South and Central America and so far it has been great.
I have been to Costa Rica only once and on vacation; It is such a beautiful country and I think we will be able to stay a few days there.
So we&#39;re excited to get our music out there.
I ask because there is a kind of devotion towards the band, the fans live with intensity the previous days.
What do they say to their most fervent supporters?
Thank you for staying by our side through all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica; Thank you for waiting so long and we&#39;re sorry it took us so long to get there.
Some people even refer to their concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a bit of pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we&#39;ve played in the last 21 years have happened in the last couple of weeks.
We played a couple of gigantic shows in Sao Paulo and hopefully that got us in shape for this show in Costa Rica.
We&#39;re really looking forward to playing there.
We love that country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both things, Costa Rica is among the best in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its waves to surf?
We have many friends who are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves there are incredible.
My friends always went surfing to Costa Rica and Nicaragua, along with Mexico, are great places to surf; that&#39;s how we found out about it, through people who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, they have been delivering huge shows with lots of songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we&#39;ve never played there before, so we don&#39;t have any restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to give the best possible show with a good variety of songs; we will try to play a couple of songs from each album and give our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What is this about?
I think it&#39;s partly because we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it&#39;s hard to choose which songs to play each night.
When we have two or three songs in our set list that we haven&#39;t played in a while, that keeps us focused and also keeps us surprised because it reminds us of the reasons why we liked those songs that we may have forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it also makes it more interesting for people.
With this tour, they are celebrating 20 years of experience.
Looking back, is it hard to believe how much you have accomplished?
Yes absolutely.
First of all, I think none of us imagined we&#39;d be in a big rock band and having done it for over 20 years makes it seem like a dream.
We continue to count our blessings and we are very excited that we can continue to make music together.
We all love each other and love to create music.
We are lucky to go to places in the world that we always wanted to go.
Things couldn&#39;t be better for us.
What did it mean to you to have been a fundamental part of the emergence of grunge?
It&#39;s always been an honor to be a part of that group of great bands.
We are very close to the people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It&#39;s amazing when a movement comes from a group of friends and it&#39;s something rare.
Every once in a while, a band comes out of a city, but it&#39;s much rarer when five or ten bands come out of the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be a part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year, we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour, so we&#39;re lucky to still be friends with all of them and honored to be a part of that Seattle sound that came out of it.
It&#39;s also very strange that a band like yours stays together and with the same members for so long.
Yeah, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which on its own is much longer than many bands last.
First, I think we&#39;re all lucky to still be alive, and second, we all care about each other.
We are all very close friends and, thanks to that, musical avenues have also opened up that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other with each other&#39;s music and it couldn&#39;t be better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been easy; however, thanks to their success, they have been able to do whatever they want.
How do you find a balance?
As we have grown, it has been easier to find a balance.
We make sure that we don&#39;t tour too much because it&#39;s easy to fall for that game of big crowds and people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are there for the music, that reminds you to respect the music and what brought it, without being infatuated with being famous and being a rock star, which none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote really good songs and at first it was kind of great.
We were a band for almost three years and we never put out a record until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There was a lot of frustration that it lasted so long and the most important thing is that we are still very good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who started in the band with us and when I hear a song or see a picture I think of what an amazing person Andy is. it was and how it made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh, talk about music and soccer and much more.
He was an amazing human being and we miss him.
The national band Las Robertas will be in charge of opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that&#39;s why you chose her for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos with various proposals and that was the band that we liked the most, so we are looking forward to seeing what Las Robertas can offer live and it must be very entertaining.
Why do they always change the lyrics for Yellow Ledbetter live?
That&#39;s a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don&#39;t know.
He sings it and I think he does it with the first thing that comes to mind.
As a bassist, what are your influences?
There are so many.
Among the first that come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, CJ Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I love.
How has Pearl Jam managed to keep grunge relevant despite not being a fad anymore?
I think all of us always feel a bit disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I mentioned before, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the bands that came out at the same time, and if there&#39;s relevance now, I think it&#39;s a wonderful thing because it&#39;s music worth listening to and bands worth listening to. like Mudhoney are now making better music than ever.
At first, his music had a darker content and now it has become more positive.
Why the change?
It&#39;s interesting because I think there are a couple of songs on the new album that maybe seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe that qualify as very dark songs even though they might sound a bit positive.
With both, when Ed played them for me, I cried when I heard them and they are deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and there&#39;s some trauma in your life and you lose a family member or a friend, those things start to influence your art and your music and those two songs definitely represent that to me.
Also, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make music that is dark.
