Fujimori is admitted again for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to be evaluated for the loss of muscle strength in his legs, his family doctor reported.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed during his government (1990-2000), suffers from various ailments, including tongue cancer for which he has undergone surgery four times and that is kept under control.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal doctor, told Canal N television that Fujimori will be evaluated for three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the reason for the pain and loss of strength in his lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori would be a candidate to obtain the benefit of pardon for humanitarian reasons, however, he said that he does not want it because he knows he is innocent.
He underwent surgery four times for cancer of the tongue, has a weight loss of 18 kilos to which other pathologies have been added such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cyst, kidney stones, arterial hypertension and problems circulatory system in the legs, listed the doctor.
Fujimori has been in prison since September 2007 in the National Directorate of Special Operations of the police.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people at the hands of an army assassination squad that operated clandestinely in the first years of his government.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation, headed by Uruguayan President José Mujica, and made up of various ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday in order to expand trade between the two nations and address political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, the highest point of an extensive agenda of meetings with political and commercial authorities and a meeting with the community of Uruguayans residing in Mexico, according to the agenda released by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents, in the city of Guadalajara, will be &quot;propitious for the exchange of information in all political affairs between the two nations,&quot; according to what the Presidency of the South American country published on its website.
According to local media, Mujica would seek to get Calderón to support Uruguay in the incident with France that arose when the French president, Nicolas Sarkozy, included the South American country in a list of tax havens, at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that continue to be tax havens, a statement that provoked the rejection of Uruguay and the call to consult its ambassador in the European country.
Since November, Mexico has chaired the G20, a group made up of the most powerful emerging and developed countries in the world, and has had an agreement in force with the South American country since January of this year to exchange tax information in order to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has tried in recent years to expedite the completion of tax exchange agreements in order to get off the &quot;grey list&quot; of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), made up of countries that have not implemented all the international standards of cooperation in tax matters.
On the commercial front, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in force since 2004, which has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations.
The mustachioed plumber goes all three dimensions with &quot;Super Mario 3D Land&quot;
Super Mario has fought tirelessly for 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but never before has he done so in three dimensions: in &quot;Super Mario 3D Land&quot; he will fight for the love of the girl in stereoscopic technology
Hitting stores around the world this month, the title has been designed from the ground up to take advantage of the features of the Nintendo 3DS handheld system, which allows for glasses-free 3D gaming.
&quot;Mario is the character who has to say how stereoscopy should work without glasses,&quot; said Nintendo&#39;s specialized press officer in Spain, Omar Álvarez, during the presentation of the video game in Madrid.
Álvarez indicated that &quot;Super Mario 3D Land&quot; is &quot;Nintendo&#39;s first video game originally designed for that support&quot;, since until now hits like &quot;Star Fox 64 3D&quot; or &quot;Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D&quot; were adaptations of existing titles.
The Nintendo spokesman has maintained that, despite being in 3D, &quot;Super Mario 3D Land&quot; is an &quot;accessible&quot; video game that allows you to enjoy a fast and fluid game.
Álvarez has affirmed that &quot;Super Mario 3D Land&quot; contains two games in one: the first part is &quot;simple&quot; to hook less skilled users.
Once passed, the most expert will be able to give a &quot;second turn&quot; to the game levels, which this time present greater difficulty.
In addition, users will be able to choose in real time between an &quot;aggressive D&quot; or one that only affects the depth of the action, but it will be necessary to play in three dimensions in order to overcome the different challenges and &quot;not succumb to optical illusions&quot;.
This incursion of Super Mario into three dimensions also means the return of the character to a portable console, a fact that has not occurred since 2005.
In this video game, Nintendo winks at fans of the saga and repeats the formula for the success of previous installments, consisting of the plumber with the mustache having to go through platforms full of dangers in order to free Princess Peach.
Although the player will find novelties in the movements, environments, costumes and enemies and also a &quot;playable&quot; Luigi.
Colom endorses Portillo&#39;s extradition to the United States
President Álvaro Colom announced on Tuesday that he has processed the extradition of ex-governor Alfonso Portillo so that he can answer in the United States for the conspiracy to launder US$70 million.
Thus ends the process for Guatemala to respond to the request of the northern country that claimed Portillo to try him there.
In a press conference, Colom affirmed that his decision obeys the independence of the judicial and executive powers, taking into account that a sentencing court had already ordered the extradition.
He asserted that during his tenure he &quot;did not get his hands on&quot; judicial resolutions and processed all the extraditions he has known.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín will be extradited, for murder and serious injuries, and Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
What Colom did is an executive process after all judicial and constitutional instances have been exhausted to prosecute the former president between 2000 and 2004.
In accordance with resolutions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court (CC), Portillo must be extradited once his legal situation in Guatemala has been resolved and his human rights are guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted for the embezzlement of Q120 million in the Ministry of Defense when he was president, which was the process that preceded the extradition, but the Public Ministry appealed and reactivated the case.
Trinijove has helped 6,000 young people at risk
The entity was born to avoid the fall into the marginality of boys without training
The balance of the first 25 years of life of the Trinijove social support entity is important: 6,000 young people at risk of exclusion have received help to overcome a difficult situation throughout this quarter of a century.
To this is added the hundred or so jobs currently achieved for this social group.
The anniversary was used yesterday to take stock in an act held in the old Fabra i Coats factory complex which was attended by more than 300 people.
Trinijove was born in the Trinitat Vella neighborhood in 1986 with the aim of helping young people with little training, without work, with drug addiction problems or in a situation of falling into marginality.
Yesterday&#39;s celebration in Sant Andreu brought together a large number of heads of entities and institutions that have collaborated with the association in these 25 years.
The varied political representation, in full electoral time, showed the unitary nature of the work carried out by Trinijove.
Together with the President of the Generalitat, Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol, the former Socialist Education Minister, Ernest Maragall, and the former Mayor and current ecosocialist councilor Ricard Gomà attended the event.
Also present in the great hall of Fabra i Coats were the current Minister for Social and Family Welfare, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the general director of La Caixa&#39;s social work, Jaume Lanaspa.
Mas affirmed that Trinijove was born in very difficult times and that the current one is also difficult, but added that the work carried out up to now &quot;is a good base&quot;.
The president gave Trinijove an example for knowing how to fight against bad circumstances and for giving hope to people in difficulties.
&quot;The crisis is not something new for the entity and for the work it does,&quot; he said.
Evicted a squatted farm where macro parties were held
The invaders had taken over 11 of the 13 floors of the building, in Balmes, 51
The 12 occupants left the farm at noon yesterday without offering resistance
Everything seems to indicate that the nightmare lived by the residents of 51 Calle de Balmes has come to an end.
Twelve people voluntarily left the property they were illegally occupying yesterday at noon, and where they organized macro-parties that made the neighborhood desperate, by court order and without the need for police intervention.
When the operation was finished, the lock on the door was changed to prevent a repeat of the situation.
&quot;From now on there will be access control,&quot; said the administrator.
The squatters, who had invaded 11 of the 13 floors of the building -the rest are inhabited-, took the entire electrical installation and part of the water installation, as well as painting the walls and leaving all kinds of waste, especially drink cans. alcoholic.
The first three floors were the scene of massive parties, which lasted up to two days and made the tenants desperate.
Next to the building there is a nightclub, Balmes 51, which has also been damaged.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat explained to Europa Press that since the building was occupied, business has dropped by 80%.
The owner of the nightclub points out that the invaders of the farm made unfair competition, since they sold the drinks for three euros, while in the nightclub they are worth 10.
In addition, the owner of the entertainment venue had had to respond to neighborhood complaints about noise, while, as she pointed out, the disturbances are not caused by the clients of the nightclub, but by the inhabitants of the squatted house and, above all, those who attend the parties that were organized there, which had increased in frequency and intensity in recent weeks, according to angry residents of the area.
The person in charge of the nightclub explained that the inconvenience was so great that she even reached an agreement with the owner of the property and for nine months she &quot;forgives&quot; the rent.
The Urban Guard also confirmed that in recent weeks it had received more complaints from neighbors about the situation.
The president of the municipal group of the PP in the town hall, Alberto Fernández Díaz, had demanded last week &quot;to immediately vacate the property to end the problems of coexistence and civility that produce the neighbors, as well as the degradation of the area&quot; .
The popular leader explained that before the summer there was only one floor of the building occupied, but over the last few months the squatters had been entering all the floors of the building and almost all the floors, and that there have even been robberies.
In this sense, he added that &quot;it is necessary to put an end to impunity and be forceful against the incivility that has been generated on the farm.&quot;
Also yesterday, the Mossos evicted a building in Nou Barris.
At 3:30 p.m., the police went to 35 Mont-ral Street, after receiving a call from a neighbor who had observed that four people were entering the building.
All four were arrested at the time.
Park or mountain?
The architects agree on the opportunity of the call beyond controversy over fees
The municipal competition for the 16 doors reopens the debate on the role of Collserola in Barcelona
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the now extinct Barcelona Metropolitan Corporation (CMB), this Administration printed some promotional flyers for Collserola.
The brochure defined the mountain as the great park of metropolitan Barcelona.
What&#39;s more, it was accompanied by a comparison, in figures, with New York&#39;s Central Park.
With the death of the CMB, in 1987, the park returned to its position, in the imagination of many, as the upper limit of Barcelona, being the Catalan capital one of the few that is not oriented on the north-south axis but rather up (mountain ) -down (sea).
The classification of Collserola as a natural park redounds to this idea.
The reference was no longer Central Park but Yellowstone, with the wild boars in the role of Yogi Bear.
In these they were until, in September, the city council called a mega-competition made up of 16 competitions for as many access doors to Collserola.
A door refers to the idea of a park, without a doubt.
Either that or someone intends to put doors to the field.
The question comes out on its own: Collserola, park or mountain?
The competition, both for its purely organizational aspect and for what it means to reflect on the city, is the topic of conversation among all Barcelonan architects.
It is almost a recurring theme to use when two members of this ancient caste of chosen ones recognize each other in an elevator.
And this fact gives rise, precisely, to one of the few coincidences between what three Barcelonan architects think, and university professors, who have presented themselves.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Mòdol and Marta Bayona: the contest is timely.
For Roldán, after addressing the coastal front &quot;it becomes necessary&quot; to discuss &quot;the mountain front&quot;, since Ildefons Cerdà&#39;s speech, that of the green apples, has not been carried out.
&quot;It should be assumed that the largest park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things because of its great accessibility.
Collserola is more complex&quot;, says the architect, for whom the title of &quot;Collserola gates&quot; contains a &quot;lexical trap&quot;: you should not think of them &quot;as the accesses to a park, but rather the delimitation of areas where you have to act &quot;.
Mòdol, like Roldán and Bayona with experience in the urban world, describes the proposal as an &quot;intellectual challenge&quot; with &quot;some dangers&quot;.
Dangers derived from how &quot;uncertain it is today to project public space&quot; after the experience lived in the 80s and that had &quot;its swan song&quot; in the Forum area.
The first fear is the very delimitation of borders on where you can build.
&quot;Limiting something is already fixing the next step&quot;, that is, its surpassing.
&quot;You have to think about new urban planning instruments, because the current ones [in reference to the General Metropolitan Plan (PGM)] can lead to real disasters.&quot;
Closer to the question, Mòdol believes that, simplifying, the Collserola side of Valles &quot;can be understood as a park, the Barcelona side, not&quot;, for a purely topographical issue.
Mòdol recalls that there is already work done by the Patronat de Collserola that &quot;should not fall on deaf ears&quot;, although he appreciates the opportunity that the council offers his union to intervene in this project &quot;from the very beginning&quot;.
And even more, he understands that the proximity of the mountain to the city is the safe-conduct that allows architects to enter the debate, but he &quot;doubts&quot; about whether it is this technical profile that should lead the multidisciplinary teams (&quot;a complete success&quot; , he points out) that have had to be created: &quot;Architects should only be a tool&quot;.
Bayona hints that the answer to the question that gives this piece its title is complex, because the contest rules lack a global vision of Collserola: &quot;16 transversal contests have been called -he says- in the mountain-sea direction, but there is no a longitudinal reading, that sees and understands the area as a whole&quot;.
