Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash where the Secretary of the Interior, Francisco Blake, and seven other people lost their lives
The Ministry of Communications and Transportation (SCT) reported that the results of the accident where the Secretary of the Interior, Francisco Blake Mora, and seven other people lost their lives, indicate that the helicopter directly impacted the ground in complete integrity. structural, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transportation, mentioned that before taking off the aircraft, the pilot verified that the weather conditions were adequate for flying.
&quot;The elements that seem to indicate that the unit had several contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage.&quot;
He also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it had the necessary requirements to transport the personnel.
In addition, he said that in the investigations carried out in the impact zone, the appearance of pieces on the ground is not reported.
&quot;In a search, it is reported that there are no parts or components of the ship in another place, the impact was structural.
&quot;The design of the helicopter was for 19 passengers, it had adequate requirements to transport the passengers.
The land presents a slope of seven degrees at 30 degrees of inclination.
For now, the secretary assured that it is a priority to have the results as soon as possible; however, the investigation can last several months, it could even last a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, general director of Airports and Auxiliary Services, assured that at the moment of impact, the helicopter of the Presidential General Staff was operating at cruising speed and that this happened on soft ascending ground.
&quot;This information strengthens the hypothesis of a normal cruise operation at the moment of impact,&quot; he said.
At the press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant elements in the investigation:
visual flight:
In accordance with aeronautical regulations, the flight was carried out under visual flight rules, this implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and the terrain.
Weather conditions:
The reports in the AICM located adequate conditions for takeoff, as the aircraft advanced towards the border area between the DF and the State of Mexico, there were layers of cloudiness at low altitude.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the cloudy conditions, the crew sought an area of lower elevation and greater visibility towards the Cuernavaca valley.
Impact location.
The impact coordinates and the last radar record of the aircraft coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration in the flight path.
Dispersal of aircraft debris in a small area:
The information available up to now allows us to assume that the impact occurred in a straight and sideways trajectory.
The pattern of dispersion of aircraft debris allows us to assume that the helicopter impacted the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No evidence of fire or explosion detected:
At the site of the accident, no evidence of any type of explosion or fire has been revealed in the remains of the ship.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that he may have had multiple contacts with the terrain.
During field work, parts of the aircraft have been found at an elevation of 9,200 feet above mean sea level, the terrain presents a slope that goes from seven degrees to 30 degrees.
The photographs show the sequence in which it was predictably dismantled along said journey.
The information provides elements that seem to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After a meticulous search in an area larger than the cordoned off site, around the accident, no scattered pieces of the aircraft have been found, which strengthens the presumption that the impact occurred in conditions of structural integrity.
MSS announces protocol to find obesity gene
Social Security directs an investigation to discover the obesity gene in children and young people; is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people, called the &#39;Genetics of childhood and adolescent obesity&#39; protocol, which will make it possible to have markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the investigation, the population is invited to participate, whether or not they have rights, to go to the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out on minors, every Saturday from 8:00 a.m. hours.
He stressed that the protocol began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Western Mexico State) and that since October 8, the activity has been carried out at the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Eastern Mexico State).
Once the objective of gathering 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Independencia Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (in the north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and the importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and youth to prevent the appearance of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day is celebrated this November 14, he specified that the objective is to bring together three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific questionnaires on nutrition .
They will also be asked about physical activity and hereditary family history of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturdays anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure measurement, determination of glucose, triglyceride, cholesterol and insulin and genetic levels (seeking to identify genes that are associated with to childhood obesity).
Cruz López pointed out that this investigation is due to the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain in minors.
&#39;The health surveys of 1999 and 2006 indicated that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 percent in obesity, and of girls of 47 percent; in terms of overweight, a dramatic rise was also observed,&#39; highlighted the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the country&#39;s population differs from others due to its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65 percent American Indian, 30 percent European, and 5 percent African heritage, and this condition is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and excess weight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy that we consume (calories) and that is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive evaluation of the children, which makes it possible to detect whether they are overweight or obese.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm, which indicate the probability that he suffers from metabolic disorders and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, the doctors deliver it in writing to the parents, who are explained each of the measurements and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity, and other chronic conditions: a sedentary lifestyle, which is the lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day sitting in front of the television, and using means of transportation instead of walking long distances. short.
It is also due to the high caloric intake, that is, the greater consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with a high fat and protein content, and the genetics that are analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid potholes
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at UNAM&#39;s Faculty of Chemistry, develops polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mix with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals sent by the pavement were heeded, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 potholes each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at UNAM&#39;s Faculty of Chemistry (FQ). who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt pavement is adequate, the potholes could be reduced in number or even completely eliminated.
In his conference A technological opinion on potholes, delivered within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he revealed that the laboratory he is in charge of develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with a greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of petroleum, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some with high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others with low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists of the fact that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius it presents an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but rather it changes during the day according to the environmental and temperature conditions, warned the specialist in chemical engineering.
The CF researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which is made up of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt layer, made up of small stones dipped in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the little stones that make up the folder, he pointed out, is coated with asphalt.
When passing vehicles and generating efforts, it allows the forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt, it would spread even better, said the chemical engineer.
On top of the asphalt layer, he added, a last layer called the rolling layer is placed, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As it is the layer that will be in contact with the tires of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide friction on the road.
As it is the part of the pavement that is going to receive and spread the stresses, the surface layer also needs to have the appropriate thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken care of.
The weather, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it considerably affects the performance of the asphalt layer.
When the ground becomes wet, the water diffuses inside the mat and it is difficult for it to come out, this causes a softening of all the layers of the pavement and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
In the process of formation of a pothole, he said, the first to wear is the film of bearing and only later is the asphalt layer affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, rather it is a process that should be addressed at the first signs with adequate maintenance programs.
The also member of the National System of Investigators explained that the vehicular load is another important factor in the formation of potholes and, therefore, the thickness of each of the pavement layers must always be in relation to the vehicular load and guarantee that comply, to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries and allow potholes to be repaired easily and without the need to use high temperatures.
