This was the work of the man from Cali who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A lofoscopist from Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of &quot;Alfonso Cano&quot;.
The work of these officials is key.
On November 4, a lofoscopist from the CTI of Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the identity of the top chief of the Farc: &quot;Alfonso Cano&quot;, through the comparison of his fingerprints.
Of the seven lofoscopists who work in the CTI section, that week it was the turn of &quot;availability&quot; for Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the judicial investigation area for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in municipalities in Chocó, where he often had to go into the jungle for more than five days to reach the place where the corpses that had to be identified were located.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of the Valley and, after completing the corresponding courses, he specialized in lofoscopia, which is the study of friction skin, that is, the palms of the hands and feet.
The week of the operation against aliases Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was warned to wear at least three days&#39; clothing.
Something big was waiting for him.
On Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected to be the man who led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so they asked him to bring the tenprint card of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the investigation team at the place where the body was found, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, as it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He was beardless, dressed like a local farmer, without glasses, and much thinner.
But the prints don&#39;t lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a transplanter, and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints on the corpse with those on the card.
His eye did not fail him: it was &quot;Alfonso Cano&quot;.
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of confirming to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was indeed the top commander of the Farc.
In search of the trace
For a dactiloscopist from the Sijín de Cali, the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Eliazar González, at the press conference for the operation against &quot;Cano&quot;, is very significant.
Many people do not know our work.
Fingerprinting is an exact science, with no margin for error, which can become key in solving crimes.
Apart from the identification of corpses, the lofoscopistas support investigations for crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of the people captured.
When caught, many criminals present false IDs or do not have papers.
We take their fingerprints and look them up in the database.
The investigator said that, in a case of theft, he had to remove a piece of the wall from a house, since the thief had placed his hand in that place to remove a safe full of jewelry and money.
&quot;The walls are difficult because they are not appropriate surfaces to take a fingerprint, but in this case we were able to obtain the print of the entire hand and identify the offender, who had participated in different thefts,&quot; he recalled.
Fingerprints can also rule out or confirm suspects in homicide cases.
They recently found a dead man, with liquor bottles around him.
Through the investigation it was determined that a relative could be suspected of the crime and, indeed, a print on the bottle matched.
Although this does not guarantee that it was the murderer, it does place him at the scene of the crime.
A CTI dactyloscopist explained that on the objects &quot;the prints are taken with chemical or physical reagents.&quot;
When they appear, a transplanter or tape is used to lift them.
After this, the impressions are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the Registry.
&quot;The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians,&quot; said the CTI expert.
He clarified that not everything is as shown on the CSI television show.
Just as not everything that glitters is gold, not everything that is touched becomes a footprint.
However, if it can be used, if the respective comparison is made.
