Japan is reborn after the earthquake
GDP grows 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and puts an end to the downward spiral that began in March
Since last March the Japanese economy had been paralyzed, still convalescing from the devastating earthquake that led to a nuclear crisis, the worst catastrophe that the Japanese country suffered since World War II.
The first estimates of the Government of Tokyo put material losses at 300,000 million dollars, a blow that, despite the difficult world context, seems to have attenuated.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, the data for the Gross Domestic Product between July and September served to definitively turn the page: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% in the annualized rate.
The one registered in the second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also represents the highest rate of growth since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is explained, in part, by the increase in the purchase of machinery to restore the areas devastated by the earthquake and the subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% decrease in capital expenditures that was observed from January to March, the first setback after six months of uninterrupted increases.
However, the true revulsion of the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that invites us to take advantage of crises to reinforce - or rebuild - infrastructures, use deficiencies to grow from scratch.
Japan has woken up, above all, thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently represents 60% of Japan&#39;s GDP.
This variable climbed 1%, driven by the increase in spending on vehicles, travel and leisure activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo has entrusted itself to the internal market, when the yen - the Japanese currency - has become one of the &quot;safe haven values&quot; chosen by investors fleeing the debt crisis in the euro zone and the murky forecasts for the US. ., a privilege that weighs heavily on the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger currency, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic waterline is determined by the health of big tech groups.
