Energetic politics:
facts must be worth more than dogmas
If there is a topic that cannot be dealt with taking into account short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is appropriate that an electoral meeting is the moment to reflect on such questions and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it looks at the full economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7,000 million people on the planet, demographic trends will mean that electricity demand will double before 2050, unless a huge part of the world&#39;s population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, it will be necessary to alleviate the increasing scarcity of fossil resources to continue producing electricity continuously, without forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to fight climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the debate. ecological.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany stands alone in its decision to give up nuclear power.
This is not the case neither in Belgium, which submits its power to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, nor in Switzerland, which only aims to build state-of-the-art plants.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name a few examples, are forging ahead with their projects with determination.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resuming the construction of a plant that was interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, based on renewable energy, is sometimes presented as an example, reality goes against such discourse.
Choosing Berlin is going to lead to an increase in the price of electricity, greater energy dependence due to the increased need for imported gas, particularly from Russia, and an increase in CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal power plants.
In a few months, the detrimental effects will be noticeable.
The case of Denmark should be considered.
Champion of Europe in the wind sector, from which it obtains 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the large users of coal and gas due to the intermittency of the wind; For this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are, respectively, 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbors pay an electricity bill 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear power would mean a sharp rise in the price of electricity, making the wonderful statements about reindustrializing our country and defending our purchasing power less realistic.
This is a price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, show no principled opposition to such energy, polls show.
Let us remember that the energy policy of our country has lost building an industrial sector with 125,000 director jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Widely export-oriented, it encompasses a galaxy of SMEs specialized in international markets and that can create non-relocatable jobs.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would mean the sacrifice of a large part of these SMEs and the loss of 6,000 million euros a year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrician would commission an EPR designed to function for sixty years, when the collapse of its manufacturer is foreseen?
To solve the nuclear power equation, one must admit that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no devilish source.
Areva&#39;s development of low CO2, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a Safety Authority that exercises strict and transparent control over both the existing plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, of recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with security.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, at Three Mile Island, was produced under normal operating conditions; It caused no consequences for people or the environment.
At Chernobyl, the accident was due to the design of the reactor and some inexcusable human error.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was the result of two natural catastrophes of unprecedented scope, killing tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, just as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to these advances and a cooperation between the safety authorities, and the French and German operators and manufacturers, the EPR presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
While being studied by all electricity players who want to build a plant, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for the competitors of Areva and EDF, since it would free them to assume the leadership in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow emotion, dogmas and partisan maneuvers to dominate a debate so important to the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy applied by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various points of view: the saturation of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of &quot;country of rights humans&quot; from France.
More recently, it is the administrative bullying of foreign students that has made headlines, with the Interior Minister (see Libération newspaper May 23) proclaiming in past that France &quot;does not need foreign talent, workers or waiters&quot;.
However, it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
The point is that, on this issue, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the tone by declaring in 1976 that &quot;900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country with close to two million immigrant workers&quot;, while on the left, the tone was set by Michel Rocard explaining that France &quot;cannot take care of all the misery in the world&quot; in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of the invasion of the national territory by a mob of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity with which they act towards immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande limits himself to including banalities, indicating that co-development will make it possible to solve the &quot;migration problem&quot;.
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be electorally profitable, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work summarizing the latest insights on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.) , there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migratory flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries that receive immigrants.
Limiting immigration weakens growth and hurts employment.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace national workers, particularly low-skilled ones, by pressing for lower wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are more complementary than substitutes for national workers and mainly practice professions in sectors with a lack of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and the most qualified in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for personnel.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon would find it difficult to work in a country that lacks anesthetists, the complementarity between nationals and immigrants means that the arrival of the latter has a positive influence on the salaries and employment of nationals.
Taking the above into account, Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migratory flows implies a rise in real wages in the long term of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And regardless of the fact that the diversity that immigrants bring contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there are a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel laureates, and companies like Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay, and Yahoo were founded). by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, since they contribute an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labor Organization calculates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income minus expenses) of 150,000 euros to public budgets on average throughout his life.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go looking for the growth points he was missing &quot;with his teeth&quot;.
Such teeth, which deterred immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it just needs to think about a European democracy
Democracy is a precious asset, but it is also fragile.
The European continent should be able to remember this since, although it was invented in Athens more than two thousand years ago, throughout the 20th century it has suffered the tragedies of the World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some perhaps believed that, for democracy to definitively triumph over its enemies, it would be enough to exercise the vote and in the most direct way possible.
We know, since Napoleon &quot;the Little&quot;, that it was something thought.
Universal suffrage, although it is a necessary condition for democracy, is not sufficient by itself and can even become an &quot;instrument of oppression&quot;, as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, separation and control of powers, education, Enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis we are experiencing in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is about to become a political and democratic crisis.
The palinodia of the true-false Greek referendum had, in this regard, a double revealing effect: it showed the need for a powerful return to the political sphere, but also the worrying sensation of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be reflected upon in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic battle have now shifted and that, in many cases, the Republican soldiers are no longer advancing in the right direction.
We will not gain by demanding a succession of national referendums, organized according to need and in a haphazard manner.
A blank signature to the absolute European monarch or an empty stop to the nationalist hole: what options for the citizen!
No, we do not want to pull off coups, but rather a common, full-fledged, calm and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at a European level.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal (in fact, we would not know where to end the list), because there is only one crisis, the crisis in Europe.
The whole of Europe is the one that submits to the orders of the markets and the rating agencies, than the one that suffers from its impotence and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that suffers humiliation in the international sphere.
We worry about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but it is all of Europe that is slowly losing sovereignty and, with it, each of its nations.
The most urgent thing is that popular sovereignty recovers the helm of the European project.
Because only together will Europeans be able to reduce their debt burden, free themselves from the markets and prepare their future through investment.
The way out of the crisis will require decisions at a European level that cannot be taken without total democratic legitimacy, unless it is to lead us to disaster.
After having fought for a long time against this proposal of the socialists and Jacques Delors, the whole world is now calling for European economic governance.
So be it.
But to think of it without greater political and democratic integration, and without it being experienced as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and would lead us to a new impasse.
We must assume a new stage of European construction.
To build the Republic in France, it was necessary to &quot;make&quot; republicans.
Revolution motivated by interests would not be enough.
This lesson still applies.
We must build a more economically integrated Europe.
It can only be achieved by building a more democratic Europe on the political level, a true European popular sovereignty.
To build Europe, let&#39;s make Europeans.
