The Nord Stream, the new gateway for Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe with Russia through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, amid the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, at the inauguration of the Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart from the Netherlands, Mark Rutte, have together turned the handwheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas into the network. Western Europe.
With this new pipeline, each year an additional 27.5 million cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive in Western Europe through a first pipeline of 1,224 km that connects the Saint Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second tube should be completed by the end of 2012, which will make it possible to supply a total of 55,000 million cubic meters of gas, that is, enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third tube along the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this enormous work presents an air of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will make it possible to supply gas directly to Germany, avoiding the land route through third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: it will be more difficult for them to influence Russia by threatening to cut off its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a &quot;new German-Soviet pact&quot;, referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of energy Europe, as the project has driven a wedge between eastern and western Europeans.
Russia has managed, in just five years, to make its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large consumers of gas and with increasingly limited reserves, triumph.
&quot;This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically,&quot; confirmed François Fillon during the pipeline&#39;s inauguration, demonstrating the extent to which large contracts in the gas sector are as political as they are economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of the Gazprom managers, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of steel coated with cement to protect it against the anchors of ships.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from World War II.
&quot;It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution,&quot; says Jens Müller, spokesman for the Nord Stream company.
Likewise, it was necessary to take extreme measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs about 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted along its entire length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Swedish waters, but those responsible for the project gave it up when they saw that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state-owned company to establish itself permanently in the sea off their coasts.
&quot;In the event of a fault, we will interrupt the gas flow in less than a minute,&quot; says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider a leak unlikely, since they have planned joints that are predicted to leak every 100,000 years.
Control of the state of the gas pipeline is guaranteed by an underwater robot, towed by a ship, which performs external inspections, as well as by a device that circulates inside the gas pipeline.
Shaped like a cigar, it is inserted inside the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides precise data on possible deformations of the metal.
The gas pipeline has been designed to function for fifty years without the need for any type of repair.
The circulation of the gas is guaranteed simply by the pressure.
At the beginning it is 200 bars and at the exit it is 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
It was joined by the Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a common company, called Nord Stream, in charge of building and operating the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is especially favourable.
Subsequently, Gazprom leased to said company, for a renewable period of twenty-five years, all of the gas transport capacities.
&quot;Gazprom will be paid for the full capacity, regardless of how much gas is actually transported,&quot; says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the gas pipeline has been carried out 30% with the contribution of shareholders and 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach 7,400 million euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure they will not out-invest, as Gazprom itself bears the risk of spending.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy shore lined with pine trees.
Some valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas exit door.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas upon arrival, before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has received one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a branded notebook.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people back a taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, of hours of writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular covers, its rubber, its off-white pages, as if aged by time.
However, Moleskine notebooks in their current look were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at that moment to launch a designer but distinguished notebook on the market.
Maria Sebregondi, at that time a consultant for the company, was in charge of launching the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover sidewalks.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
&quot;Moleskine has adapted to current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century,&quot; says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become head of the brand at Modo Modo.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
Gone is the confidential production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the profile of the buyer, since the notebook attracts businessmen as well as students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which had twelve employees at its inception, now has close to 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from Fnac to small shops in the center of cities, and has managed to impose his identity.
&quot;We have adapted to the times and to the need to write, despite the rise of emails&quot;, explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the &quot;Detour&quot; exhibition where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, it also launched a notebook with leopard covers, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, diaries, pens, computer cases... The brand covers a wide range of media.
An envy-inducing success: In autumn 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in Moleskine&#39;s history.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
The XV Week for the employment of the disabled begins today.
Despite a resolute public policy, applied since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people is double the average rate: 19%, compared to 9% for the population as a whole.
Discouraging?
&quot;No&quot;, affirms Éric Blanchet, general director of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
&quot;The progress achieved in the last fifteen years is considerable.
&quot;Back then, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
&quot;However, there is still a lot to do.&quot;
It is worth mentioning that the disabled unemployed continue to face many obstacles in accessing employment.
They tend to be older: 37% are over 50 (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not finished high school and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
In other words, there are numerous issues that make it particularly difficult to return to the world of work and that &quot;are the crux of the problem,&quot; says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those that are not mentioned; the mentality of the people advances, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association for the Cité pointed out that the directors surveyed have &quot;a low level of knowledge about disabilities&quot;, with an &quot;excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physically or intellectually handicapped&quot;.
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are very far from the objective of hiring 6% of disabled workers, an objective that was set in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest figures available, dating from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
&quot;Now we reach around 3%,&quot; says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the body in charge of collecting contributions from companies that do not respect this law.
The proof: the number of establishments &quot;subject to this contribution&quot;, as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, going from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
&quot;The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has created great pressure for companies,&quot; explains Pierre Blanc.
&quot;But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, particularly among large groups.&quot;
According to the Ministry of Labor, only 59% of companies with between 20 and 49 workers have disabled employees on their staff, compared to 82% of companies with between 100 and 199 workers.
Hazard: &quot;A joy&quot;
About to face Les Bleus on Tuesday evening (8:45 pm), Eden Hazard and Georges Leekens do not hide the pleasure that this friendly match generates for them.
We will not dare to say that there was collusion between them, but the image is symbolic.
Sitting next to each other, on the dais in the auditorium at the Stade de France, Georges Leekens and Eden Hazard have truly made amends.
Five months after his striker&#39;s grudge against Turkey, the Belgian coach has nothing but praise for him.
&quot;I was very happy for Eden, for his progress and for being Belgian.&quot;
&quot;I want to move forward,&quot; the Lille striker replies.
As for the contrast between his presentations in his team and in the national team, &quot;it is a group&quot;, it has been justified.
&quot;In Lille, I am all year round, which does not apply to Belgium.
&quot;I have to position myself.&quot;
Called up to play against Romania on Friday night, with this match against France in mind, Hazard comes to Saint-Denis to finally &quot;shine&quot;.
Without forgetting the &quot;pleasure&quot;.
He has been supporting Les Bleus since he was seven years old, as well as during the victorious campaigns of 1998 and 2000.
&quot;I&#39;ve always been his fan,&quot; he says.
Without a doubt, this will especially reinforce the &quot;particular&quot; character of the meeting.
Especially since he will face &quot;Mathieu (Debuchy), Yohan (Cabaye) and Adil (Rami)&quot;, he recalls.
&quot;We just met recently.
&quot;Playing against them is always a joy.&quot;
With simplicity, Leekens has made for his part reference to &quot;pride&quot;.
&quot;Pride&quot; for playing &quot;a gala match&quot;.
&quot;Pride&quot; also for verifying, as a &quot;neighbor&quot;, that France &quot;is once again a very high-level team&quot;, nearly a year after the Knysna trauma.
&quot;Laurent Blanc has done a tremendous job,&quot; he enthused.
While Belgium will not attend the next European competition, the coach would be delighted to be able to share a plane with Les Bleus to... Brazil, in 2014.
&quot;Our little Belgians are growing,&quot; he stressed.
&quot;We are building something; the players are ambitious, they are hungry.
&quot;They will be able to see it in the next games.&quot; Including the match against France.
Portugal shows a lot of confidence
Paulo Bento&#39;s Portugal faces the return match against Bosnia (10:00 pm) with great optimism, which will take place on Tuesday in Lisbon.
In the first leg, both teams lacked realism.
&quot;When these 90 minutes are up, we will be a happy team and, above all, a happy country.&quot;
Paulo Bento is already seen in Poland and Ukraine.
He has no doubt; the Selecçao, which he has led since September 2010, is going to qualify for Euro 2012.
Indeed, only 90 minutes separate Portugal from happiness.
But there is a game to play and a rival, Bosnia, to defeat.
Taking into account the first leg (0-0), on Friday in the hell of Zenica, it seems clear that the matter is not decided.
Portugal dominated the game for over an hour, yes, but they couldn&#39;t score the valuable goal that would have given them peace of mind.
&quot;It&#39;s a good result, but at the same time it carries a risk, since we haven&#39;t scored away from home.&quot;
But at home, in Lisbon&#39;s bright Estadio de la Luz, the Portuguese are convinced they will go through, in front of a crowd that should be just as enthusiastic, even if it is clear that the game is &quot;very close&quot;, says an optimistic but lucid.
&quot;We expect the game to be very even, but we are completely convinced that we can take the lead,&quot; said the 42-year-old Portuguese coach.
&quot;We still have a 50% chance of participating in Euro 2012,&quot; however, Carlos Queiroz&#39;s successor has relativized.
Friday&#39;s draw in Bosnia forces the Portuguese to score and win.
The Bosnians could get a draw, although they also need to score.
&quot;It&#39;s a good result, but at the same time it carries a risk, since we haven&#39;t scored away from home,&quot; laments Bento.
&quot;We are going to play against a team that has great technical quality and that has players with great individual quality,&quot; he added.
As in Zenica, the Portuguese will go with the intention of exerting, from the beginning, maximum pressure on the Bosnians to &quot;not leave them time to think.&quot;
A good idea, as long as, this time, it is realistic.
